Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.69,0:00:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Welcome to the June 2019 program\Nof JW Broadcasting.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.08,0:00:26.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Earlier this year,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.81,0:00:29.11,Default,,0,0,0,,56 students from all over the world
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.11,0:00:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,gathered to attend
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.61,0:00:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the Watchtower Bible School of Gilead.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.28,0:00:36.45,Default,,0,0,0,,They enjoyed a 20-week course that gifted them
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.45,0:00:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,with an in-depth study of the Bible.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.62,0:00:41.82,Default,,0,0,0,,The aim of Gilead schooling
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.83,0:00:45.17,Default,,0,0,0,,is to help strengthen\Nthe faith of each of the students
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.16,0:00:49.77,Default,,0,0,0,,so that they in turn can strengthen\Nthe brothers in their respective assignments.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.70,0:00:52.70,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 9 of this year,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.70,0:00:56.77,Default,,0,0,0,,the graduation program for the 146th class
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.77,0:00:59.64,Default,,0,0,0,,was held at the Watchtower Educational Center
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.64,0:01:01.98,Default,,0,0,0,,in Patterson, New York.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.98,0:01:04.75,Default,,0,0,0,,You’ll now enjoy faith-strengthening talks
Dialogue: 0,0:01:04.75,0:01:07.49,Default,,0,0,0,,that were delivered during the first part
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.48,0:01:09.55,Default,,0,0,0,,of the Gilead graduation program.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.62,0:01:12.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’re happy to be here today
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.66,0:01:17.70,Default,,0,0,0,,for this graduation of the 146th class of Gilead,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.69,0:01:20.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and we welcome all who are tied in with us
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.50,0:01:23.90,Default,,0,0,0,,at our Bethel complexes in the United States,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.90,0:01:26.34,Default,,0,0,0,,in Canada, in Puerto Rico,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.34,0:01:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,and in a number of remote translation offices.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.24,0:01:32.58,Default,,0,0,0,,We especially welcome our Gilead students
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.58,0:01:36.65,Default,,0,0,0,,who are about to graduate\Nfrom this marvelous school.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.65,0:01:39.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And we welcome your dear family members
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.38,0:01:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,and friends who are joining you\Non this very, very special day.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.39,0:01:47.43,Default,,0,0,0,,You seem excited, and you should be.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.42,0:01:50.99,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re happy.\NWe’re very, very happy for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.99,0:01:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, throughout your schooling,\Nyou’ve been asked to draw out principles
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.76,0:01:58.83,Default,,0,0,0,,from many different Bible accounts, haven’t you?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.84,0:02:03.78,Default,,0,0,0,,With that in mind,\Nhere’s the theme of our introductory comments:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.77,0:02:08.64,Default,,0,0,0,,“Do You See the Point\Nand Remember the Purpose?”
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.65,0:02:11.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to illustrate what we mean
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.01,0:02:15.92,Default,,0,0,0,,by looking at Luke 5:1-11.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.92,0:02:19.69,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the account\Nwhere some of Jesus’ disciples
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.69,0:02:23.73,Default,,0,0,0,,chose to leave everything behind\Nand follow him.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.73,0:02:25.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Here’s the setting:
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.73,0:02:28.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of Jesus’ disciples were fishermen
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.63,0:02:31.50,Default,,0,0,0,,who had followed Jesus for a time,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.50,0:02:34.34,Default,,0,0,0,,but then they went back to their fishing business.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.34,0:02:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus sought to reach their hearts
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.94,0:02:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and move them to follow him fully.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.68,0:02:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did he do?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.68,0:02:45.35,Default,,0,0,0,,He used a powerful object lesson
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.35,0:02:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,that provided a point and a purpose.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.48,0:02:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s read it at Luke 5:1-11,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.12,0:02:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and look for the point, first of all,\Nbehind what Jesus did here.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.96,0:03:05.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: “On one occasion\Nwhen the crowd was pressing in on him
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.10,0:03:07.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“and listening to the word of God,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.70,0:03:10.60,Default,,0,0,0,,“he was standing by the lake of Gennesaret.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.61,0:03:13.78,Default,,0,0,0,,“And he saw two boats docked at the lakeside,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.78,0:03:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,“but the fishermen had got out of them\Nand were washing off their nets.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.88,0:03:21.05,Default,,0,0,0,,“Going aboard one of the boats,\Nwhich was Simon’s,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.05,0:03:23.85,Default,,0,0,0,,“he asked him to pull away a bit from land.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.85,0:03:28.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then he sat down,\Nand he began teaching the crowds from the boat.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.86,0:03:31.96,Default,,0,0,0,,“When he stopped speaking,\Nhe said to Simon:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.96,0:03:36.67,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Pull out to where it is deep,\Nand let down your nets for a catch.’
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.67,0:03:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,“But in reply Simon said:
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.94,0:03:42.61,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Instructor, we toiled all night and caught nothing,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.61,0:03:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“but at your word I will lower the nets.’
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.24,0:03:49.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“Well, when they did this,\Nthey caught a great number of fish.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.21,0:03:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“In fact, their nets began ripping apart.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.55,0:03:56.69,Default,,0,0,0,,“So they motioned to their partners\Nin the other boat to come and assist them,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.69,0:04:01.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“and they came and filled both boats,\Nso that these began to sink.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.16,0:04:05.20,Default,,0,0,0,,“Seeing this, Simon Peter\Nfell down at the knees of Jesus,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.19,0:04:09.80,Default,,0,0,0,,“saying: ‘Depart from me, Lord,\Nbecause I am a sinful man.’
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.80,0:04:14.10,Default,,0,0,0,,“For both he and those with him\Nwere overwhelmed with astonishment
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.10,0:04:16.70,Default,,0,0,0,,“at the catch of fish they had taken,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.71,0:04:21.21,Default,,0,0,0,,“and the same was true\Nof both James and John, Zebedee’s sons,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.21,0:04:23.25,Default,,0,0,0,,“who were partners with Simon.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.25,0:04:25.32,Default,,0,0,0,,“But Jesus said to Simon:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.32,0:04:27.36,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Stop being afraid.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.35,0:04:30.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“From now on you will be catching men alive.’
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.79,0:04:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“So they brought the boats back to land
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.39,0:04:37.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and abandoned everything and followed him.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.70,0:04:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what was the point
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.60,0:04:44.50,Default,,0,0,0,,behind this miracle here?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.50,0:04:46.04,Default,,0,0,0,,What was this?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.04,0:04:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Their needs would be cared for
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.57,0:04:52.51,Default,,0,0,0,,if they trusted in Jesus and followed him.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.51,0:04:56.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, to do this,\Nthey had to believe Jesus, didn’t they?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.45,0:04:57.65,Default,,0,0,0,,They had to listen to him.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.65,0:04:59.49,Default,,0,0,0,,This was not a trick.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.48,0:05:02.95,Default,,0,0,0,,With their own eyes,\Nthey could see that catch of fish
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.95,0:05:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and then deduce that their needs would,\Nin fact, be cared for by Jesus.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.82,0:05:09.39,Default,,0,0,0,,That was the point.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.39,0:05:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Did they get it?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.89,0:05:12.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, they did.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.33,0:05:13.53,Default,,0,0,0,,With what result?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.53,0:05:16.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it says that they\Nwere moved to abandon everything
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.87,0:05:19.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and follow Jesus
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.17,0:05:21.57,Default,,0,0,0,,—that is,\Neverything related to the fishing business.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.57,0:05:24.84,Default,,0,0,0,,They gave it all up and followed him.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.84,0:05:29.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Almost instantly,\Ntheir faith and trust in Jesus grew, didn’t it?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.65,0:05:33.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s bring the point up to our day.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.52,0:05:36.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon you will go to your assignments.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.89,0:05:40.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you remember the point of your Gilead training?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.49,0:05:42.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, what is the point?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.26,0:05:45.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The point has been to build up your faith
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.50,0:05:47.90,Default,,0,0,0,,and your trust in Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.90,0:05:50.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and thereby strengthen\Nyour relationship with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.57,0:05:54.17,Default,,0,0,0,,In turn,\Nas you draw steadily closer to Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.17,0:05:56.44,Default,,0,0,0,,you will be ready for whatever work
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.44,0:06:01.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and whatever responsibility\Nhe chooses to place on you.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.14,0:06:04.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah, by means of his Son, will care for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.21,0:06:07.81,Default,,0,0,0,,He will help you\Nto faithfully fulfill your assignments,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.82,0:06:10.02,Default,,0,0,0,,and you will add to his glory.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.02,0:06:12.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And in all that you do,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.19,0:06:16.36,Default,,0,0,0,,remember those disciples\Nwho were humble enough to get the point
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.36,0:06:20.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—abandon everything and follow Jesus.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.40,0:06:25.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, for the second part of the question\Nwe mentioned at the beginning,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.64,0:06:28.78,Default,,0,0,0,,What was the purpose behind what Jesus did?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.77,0:06:32.44,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words,\NJesus’ miracle on that day
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.44,0:06:35.91,Default,,0,0,0,,carried what deeper meaning for them?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.91,0:06:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, looking back at Luke chapter 5,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.71,0:06:42.38,Default,,0,0,0,,what happened\Nwhen the disciples listened to Jesus,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.39,0:06:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,went out to where the water was deep,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.49,0:06:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and lowered their nets?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.56,0:06:49.26,Default,,0,0,0,,The catch was so great that it says
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.26,0:06:52.83,Default,,0,0,0,,they filled two boats to the point of sinking.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.83,0:06:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,The account doesn’t say\Nwhat the disciples did with the fish,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.37,0:06:58.41,Default,,0,0,0,,but they made it to shore.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.40,0:07:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,A man who could walk on water\Nwas not going to let them sink.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.64,0:07:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we get, though,\Nto the greater purpose behind Jesus’ miracle.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.64,0:07:11.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you recall what Jesus said to the disciples
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.38,0:07:13.38,Default,,0,0,0,,after that catch of fish
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.38,0:07:17.95,Default,,0,0,0,,and after the disciples became filled with astonishment?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.95,0:07:21.65,Default,,0,0,0,,He told them: “Stop being afraid.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.66,0:07:25.90,Default,,0,0,0,,From now on you will be catching men alive.”
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.90,0:07:28.40,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, by means of that miracle,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.40,0:07:33.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus illustrated something\Ngreater for them, didn’t he?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.14,0:07:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,They would not only be cared for materially
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.77,0:07:37.77,Default,,0,0,0,,(they got that point)
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.77,0:07:40.84,Default,,0,0,0,,but, more importantly,\Nthey would also become
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.84,0:07:44.74,Default,,0,0,0,,very successful fishers of men.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.75,0:07:46.95,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, the first miracle
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.95,0:07:50.85,Default,,0,0,0,,pointed to an even greater one yet to come.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.85,0:07:54.39,Default,,0,0,0,,If their large catch was meant to illustrate
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.39,0:07:58.69,Default,,0,0,0,,how successful they would be as fishers of men,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.69,0:08:02.09,Default,,0,0,0,,then they could look back\Non that catch years later
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.10,0:08:05.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and visualize those boats filled with fish
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.54,0:08:08.78,Default,,0,0,0,,and be reminded\Nthat they had much work yet to do
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.77,0:08:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,in being fishers of men
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.17,0:08:16.18,Default,,0,0,0,,—“catching men alive,” so to speak,\Nand helping them to become disciples of Christ.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.25,0:08:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Your Gilead training\Nwill help you to continue supporting
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.02,0:08:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,this vital and never-to-be-repeated work,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.55,0:08:28.45,Default,,0,0,0,,which is the greater purpose behind your training.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.46,0:08:33.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So, then, whatever you’re given to do\Nand wherever your training may take you,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.40,0:08:37.80,Default,,0,0,0,,never forget the point\Nand the purpose behind the blessing
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.80,0:08:41.77,Default,,0,0,0,,that you just experienced\Nin being part of this class.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.77,0:08:46.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Trust in Jehovah and in his Son\Nto help you at all times,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.51,0:08:50.81,Default,,0,0,0,,and use your Gilead training \Nto support this important work
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.81,0:08:54.38,Default,,0,0,0,,in the branches and the territories\Nwhere you will serve.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.65,0:08:57.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we’ll say a little bit more about this
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.85,0:09:01.35,Default,,0,0,0,,at the conclusion of our program today.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.36,0:09:05.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we’re going to enjoy\Na series of very encouraging talks
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.53,0:09:08.83,Default,,0,0,0,,that will strengthen your faith,\Nbuild up your trust,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.83,0:09:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,(in fact, for all of us listening in)
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.17,0:09:13.71,Default,,0,0,0,,and highlight God’s wonderful purpose
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.70,0:09:15.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that we support.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.74,0:09:19.11,Default,,0,0,0,,To begin, we’re very happy to have with us
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.11,0:09:21.85,Default,,0,0,0,,a member of the Governing Body,\NBrother David Splane,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.84,0:09:24.18,Default,,0,0,0,,who is going to present the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.18,0:09:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,“If You Look for It, You Will Find It.”
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.27,0:09:46.67,Default,,0,0,0,,If you look for it,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.67,0:09:49.14,Default,,0,0,0,,you will find it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.14,0:09:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Look for what?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.71,0:09:56.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Look for the good in your brothers.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.45,0:09:58.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And when you find it,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.81,0:10:02.75,Default,,0,0,0,,don’t be afraid to acknowledge it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.75,0:10:05.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we all know that we should do that,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.89,0:10:08.23,Default,,0,0,0,,but we do have to fight the tendency
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.22,0:10:11.66,Default,,0,0,0,,to view others a bit critically at times.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.66,0:10:14.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes we question their motives,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.46,0:10:19.30,Default,,0,0,0,,maybe because we’re just a little bit jealous.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.47,0:10:23.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, think\Nabout that brother in your congregation
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.37,0:10:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,who is just an excellent public speaker.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.21,0:10:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,When he is scheduled to give a talk,\Nthe hall is full.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.61,0:10:33.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And everybody raves about his talks,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.35,0:10:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,even your wife
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.32,0:10:40.06,Default,,0,0,0,,—yours, not so much.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.39,0:10:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,‘The show-off; he doesn’t impress me.’
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.76,0:10:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Or what about this:
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.76,0:10:52.56,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re working in a department\Nwith one of those annoying people
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.57,0:10:55.17,Default,,0,0,0,,who is very efficient.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.41,0:10:58.41,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s never late,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.41,0:11:00.75,Default,,0,0,0,,he never misses a day’s work,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.74,0:11:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,he gets a tremendous amount done in a day,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.15,0:11:06.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and he almost never makes a mistake.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.02,0:11:10.19,Default,,0,0,0,,‘That doesn’t impress me either.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.19,0:11:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. Perfect, he’s trying to make\Nthe rest of us look bad.’
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.76,0:11:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, there we go questioning \Nsomeone’s motives.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.60,0:11:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, can we look for the good in Mr. Perfect?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.13,0:11:28.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Can we, see, give him the benefit of the doubt?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.67,0:11:32.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe his parents trained him
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.41,0:11:36.15,Default,,0,0,0,,to offer the very best gift he could to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.15,0:11:38.99,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, if he could do more,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.98,0:11:41.35,Default,,0,0,0,,he was expected to do more,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.35,0:11:43.59,Default,,0,0,0,,because he wanted his gift
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.59,0:11:46.23,Default,,0,0,0,,to be the very best gift\Nthat he could possibly give.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.22,0:11:50.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, come to think of it,\Nhe never criticizes your gift to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.76,0:11:55.26,Default,,0,0,0,,He just wants to give\Nhis very best gift to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.26,0:11:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s the way\Nhe approached the pioneer ministry,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.30,0:12:01.70,Default,,0,0,0,,and that’s the way\Nhe approaches his Bethel service.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.70,0:12:04.27,Default,,0,0,0,,So, now, what do you do with Mr. Perfect?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.27,0:12:06.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you tell him to slow down?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.91,0:12:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“You’re making the rest of us look bad.”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.75,0:12:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if he did that,\Nhe’d be giving a substandard gift to Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.75,0:12:19.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and Jehovah expects\Nand deserves the very best.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.69,0:12:21.69,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what do you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.69,0:12:24.29,Default,,0,0,0,,You acknowledge his gift.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.29,0:12:26.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“You really get a lot done in a day;
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.93,0:12:29.37,Default,,0,0,0,,I wish I had your stamina.”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.37,0:12:33.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And what about Mr. Show-off,\Nthe outstanding speaker?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.90,0:12:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah has given you a wonderful gift.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.91,0:12:39.08,Default,,0,0,0,,You use it well.”
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.07,0:12:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, was that hard?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.58,0:12:46.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Elders occasionally have to evaluate\Nbrothers for privileges of service.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.42,0:12:49.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And while we’re not blind\Nto the shortcomings of our brothers,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.79,0:12:53.06,Default,,0,0,0,,we try to keep the discussion mainly positive.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.06,0:12:57.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, sometimes we have to discuss\Na shortcoming—a negative.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.79,0:13:01.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But are we talking about one isolated incident,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.23,0:13:03.73,Default,,0,0,0,,or is it a pattern?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.73,0:13:07.27,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s true that if we make it\Na habit to look on the positive side,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.27,0:13:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,we’ll be disappointed sometimes.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.44,0:13:12.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But it’s better to be disappointed occasionally
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.71,0:13:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,than to develop a cynical or resentful attitude
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.38,0:13:19.48,Default,,0,0,0,,toward our brothers.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.48,0:13:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s consider a Scriptural example
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.92,0:13:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,where questioning the motives of a brother
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.25,0:13:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,could have led to disaster.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.49,0:13:31.56,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s in 1 Samuel chapter 17
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.56,0:13:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,—and a little bit of background,\Na little bit of the setting—
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.93,0:13:40.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesse has sent his youngest son, David,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.34,0:13:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to visit his three oldest brothers in the army,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.31,0:13:47.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and Israel is having a face-off with the Philistines.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.81,0:13:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And when he arrives, David hears Goliath
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.35,0:13:53.79,Default,,0,0,0,,challenge any man of the house of Israel
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.78,0:13:55.88,Default,,0,0,0,,to a battle to the death.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.89,0:13:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,There are no volunteers.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.09,0:14:02.19,Default,,0,0,0,,David is a man of faith, and he can’t believe it.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.19,0:14:05.69,Default,,0,0,0,,He says:\N“Who is this uncircumcised Philistine
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.69,0:14:09.46,Default,,0,0,0,,that he should taunt\Nthe battle line[s] of the living [true] God?”
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.47,0:14:12.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, his oldest brother, Eliab, is listening,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.90,0:14:15.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and we pick up the account in verse 28.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.57,0:14:18.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So that’s 1 Samuel chapter 17,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.07,0:14:20.94,Default,,0,0,0,,and we’ll read verse 28:
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.94,0:14:25.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“When his oldest brother Eliab\Nheard him speak to the men,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.01,0:14:27.91,Default,,0,0,0,,“he became [very] angry with David and said:
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.92,0:14:29.79,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘Why have you come down?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.79,0:14:32.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘And with whom did you leave\Nthose few sheep in the wilderness?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.99,0:14:35.86,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I well know your presumptuousness
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.86,0:14:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘and the bad intentions of your heart;
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:43.40,Default,,0,0,0,,you came down just to see the battle.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.40,0:14:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what did we learn\Nabout Eliab’s personality from this verse?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.04,0:14:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Not much.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.04,0:14:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,You recognize that as a trick question.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.55,0:15:01.55,Default,,0,0,0,,We just met the man,\Nwe don’t know very much about him,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.55,0:15:05.65,Default,,0,0,0,,and we certainly aren’t going to pass\Njudgment on somebody
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.65,0:15:08.89,Default,,0,0,0,,over one isolated incident, are we?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.89,0:15:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now the question is this:
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.89,0:15:15.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Was this a one-off for Eliab,\Nor was he always like that?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.26,0:15:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Was this an isolated incident, or was it a pattern?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.00,0:15:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,When analyzing the situation, ask yourself this,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.01,0:15:26.01,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Was there ever an occasion
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.01,0:15:30.98,Default,,0,0,0,,‘when I got so frustrated with my fleshly brother
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.98,0:15:33.45,Default,,0,0,0,,‘that I said something awful,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.45,0:15:36.49,Default,,0,0,0,,something that I had to apologize for later?’
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.49,0:15:39.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, did that make you a terrible person?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.39,0:15:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,So the question is:\NIs this a one-off?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.82,0:15:43.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it isolated, or is it a pattern?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.86,0:15:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,These are things that we really need to apply
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.86,0:15:48.60,Default,,0,0,0,,when it comes to our relations\Nwith our brothers and sisters.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.60,0:15:53.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t write somebody off\Non the basis of one incident.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.60,0:15:57.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we can say that on this occasion,\NEliab was wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.87,0:16:02.07,Default,,0,0,0,,He questioned David’s motives,\Nand he wasn’t nice about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.08,0:16:04.08,Default,,0,0,0,,But that’s not the worst of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.08,0:16:07.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Suppose that David had listened to Eliab saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.98,0:16:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Slow down,\Nyou’re making the rest of us look bad.’
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.79,0:16:13.79,Default,,0,0,0,,What might have happened?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.79,0:16:16.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Suppose David had said: ‘You’re right, Eliab.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.29,0:16:18.29,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I am a bit arrogant.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.29,0:16:22.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Who do I think I am\Nthat I could fight this mighty man of war?’
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.10,0:16:26.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that could have had\Ndisastrous consequences for Israel,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.30,0:16:28.34,Default,,0,0,0,,at least temporarily.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.34,0:16:30.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what’s the lesson?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.34,0:16:35.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t discourage anyone\Nfrom giving their best to Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.24,0:16:39.91,Default,,0,0,0,,even if their best is better than your best.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.92,0:16:43.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s take another isolated incident\Nfrom the life of Eliab
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.82,0:16:46.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and say something positive about the man.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.42,0:16:49.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look for the good in Eliab.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.29,0:16:51.53,Default,,0,0,0,,First Samuel 22
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.26,0:16:57.66,Default,,0,0,0,,—1 Samuel 22:1,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.60,0:17:05.14,Default,,0,0,0,,it says:\N“So David went from there,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.14,0:17:07.68,Default,,0,0,0,,“escaping to the cave of Adullam.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.68,0:17:10.55,Default,,0,0,0,,“[So David is running away from Saul.]
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.55,0:17:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,“When his brothers
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.58,0:17:17.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“and his father’s entire house heard of it,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.75,0:17:20.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“they went down there to him
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.62,0:17:24.02,Default,,0,0,0,,[his brothers, including Eliab].”
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.03,0:17:26.03,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what’s the point?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.03,0:17:29.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, when he was needed,\NEliab was there for him.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.77,0:17:31.47,Default,,0,0,0,,He could be counted on.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.47,0:17:36.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And later, one of David’s sons\Nmarried one of Eliab’s daughters.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.51,0:17:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, wait a minute, say that again.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.68,0:17:43.68,Default,,0,0,0,,David ran away from Saul?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.95,0:17:48.02,Default,,0,0,0,,He didn’t run away from Goliath, did he?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.02,0:17:50.82,Default,,0,0,0,,But he ran away from Saul.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.82,0:17:53.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s spirit must have indicated
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.69,0:17:56.53,Default,,0,0,0,,when David should stand and fight
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.53,0:18:00.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and when he should run and hide.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.20,0:18:02.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Sounds like material for another talk.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.93,0:18:07.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it’ll help our blood pressure
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.50,0:18:09.80,Default,,0,0,0,,if we can learn to give a positive spin
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.81,0:18:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,to potentially negative situations.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.81,0:18:14.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe you’ve run into this.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.81,0:18:19.55,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re walking down the hallway\Nfollowing closely behind someone.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.55,0:18:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,He goes through the door\Nand lets the door slam right in your face.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.95,0:18:30.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Is he self-centered or just lost in thought?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.63,0:18:34.33,Default,,0,0,0,,How do you choose to characterize that incident?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.33,0:18:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Is the public speaker a show-off,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.03,0:18:41.87,Default,,0,0,0,,or on this occasion is he simply trying\Na bit too hard to be enthusiastic?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.41,0:18:48.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Is the brother being picky,\Nor is he trying to be thorough?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.14,0:18:52.61,Default,,0,0,0,,standoffish and proud\Nor just shy?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.82,0:18:57.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, one day, some of you brothers\Nare going to have positions of responsibility,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.79,0:19:00.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and you’re going to be dealing with people.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.56,0:19:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And when that happens, remember this:
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.89,0:19:09.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Many joys are denied those\Nwho keep looking for mistakes,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.90,0:19:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,but the one who sees the good in others
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.50,0:19:16.87,Default,,0,0,0,,will have “a feast constantly.”
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.87,0:19:18.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember that!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.51,0:19:20.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And may Jehovah bless you richly.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.51,0:19:22.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We love you.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.89,0:19:36.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we thank you very, very much\Nfor that encouraging talk, Brother Splane.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.86,0:19:39.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we have a member \Nof the U.S. Branch Committee
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.56,0:19:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,with us to deliver the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.83,0:19:43.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“He Causes to Become.”
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.97,0:19:46.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Troy Snyder will do this for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.77,0:19:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, as Gilead graduates,\Nyou’re being sent out
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.98,0:19:57.89,Default,,0,0,0,,to strengthen and stabilize\NJehovah’s precious sheep.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.88,0:20:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And you’re being sent out
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.08,0:20:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,on the threshold of the great tribulation.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.49,0:20:09.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what one scripture will strengthen
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.06,0:20:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and stabilize you so you can help others?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.50,0:20:15.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, here’s a clue:
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.50,0:20:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,What truth did Jehovah\Nreveal to fortify the Israelites
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.47,0:20:23.41,Default,,0,0,0,,right before they\Nwere to be delivered from Egypt?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.41,0:20:27.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s turn our Bibles to Exodus chapter 3,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.11,0:20:29.85,Default,,0,0,0,,and let’s notice what truth Jehovah revealed.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.85,0:20:31.85,Default,,0,0,0,,You remember the account?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.85,0:20:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Moses was asking Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:34.95,0:20:37.75,Default,,0,0,0,,‘What can I tell the Israelites
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.75,0:20:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,so that they will have\Nconfidence in your deliverance?’
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.09,0:20:42.09,Default,,0,0,0,,In essence,\Nthat’s what he was asking Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.09,0:20:46.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what Jehovah said\Nto fortify them in verse 14:
Dialogue: 0,0:20:46.50,0:20:48.77,Default,,0,0,0,,“So God said to Moses:
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.76,0:20:52.56,Default,,0,0,0,,“‘I Will Become What I Choose to Become.’
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.57,0:20:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“And he added: \N‘This is what you are to say to the Israelites,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.57,0:21:00.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“I Will Become has sent me to you.”’”
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.74,0:21:05.38,Default,,0,0,0,,That fortified the Israelites.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.38,0:21:07.38,Default,,0,0,0,,They understood that Jehovah was saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.38,0:21:11.18,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’ll be whatever is necessary to carry out my will.’
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.96,0:21:17.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And according to Appendix A\Nin our New World Translation,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.66,0:21:20.90,Default,,0,0,0,,it appears that the name also means
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.90,0:21:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,“He Causes to Become”
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.43,0:21:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,or “He Causes\NHis Creation (you and me) to Become”
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.64,0:21:29.94,Default,,0,0,0,,whatever is needed to carry out his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.94,0:21:32.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And doesn’t that harmonize with who Jehovah is?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.77,0:21:35.01,Default,,0,0,0,,We know him as the Creator, don’t we?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.01,0:21:36.55,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s created us.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.55,0:21:38.59,Default,,0,0,0,,He brought about this universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.58,0:21:41.52,Default,,0,0,0,,He is the God who causes to become.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.95,0:21:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, this truth\N—this extraordinary truth—
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.52,0:21:49.36,Default,,0,0,0,,can strengthen and stabilize you
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.69,0:21:53.16,Default,,0,0,0,,because it links you
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.16,0:21:56.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to something that Jehovah is willing to give you.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.77,0:21:58.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s look at what that is.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.97,0:22:01.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s go to Jeremiah chapter 10.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.11,0:22:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, this aspect of Jehovah’s name
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.75,0:22:12.19,Default,,0,0,0,,reveals something about his personality
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.18,0:22:14.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and something that he’s willing to share with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.28,0:22:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what it is in verse 6, Jeremiah 10:6.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.82,0:22:21.22,Default,,0,0,0,,It says:\N“No one is like you, O Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.22,0:22:23.22,Default,,0,0,0,,“You are great,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.23,0:22:25.30,Default,,0,0,0,,“and your name
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.29,0:22:29.16,Default,,0,0,0,,is great and mighty.”
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.16,0:22:33.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Jehovah’s name is linked to his power.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.04,0:22:35.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s what it reveals about Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.67,0:22:40.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And Jehovah is willing to use\Nhis power to strengthen us.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.14,0:22:43.84,Default,,0,0,0,,See, it was Jehovah’s power\Nthat caused the Red Sea to part.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.85,0:22:48.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It was Jehovah’s power that made\Nthe sun stand still when Joshua was in battle.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.52,0:22:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,It was Jehovah’s power\Nthat caused a bird to feed Elijah.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.52,0:22:56.69,Default,,0,0,0,,It was Jehovah’s power
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.69,0:22:59.63,Default,,0,0,0,,that took a tired prophet who was exhausted
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.63,0:23:02.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and made him run faster than a racing chariot.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.96,0:23:05.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn’t that reassuring\N—to know that Jehovah is saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.93,0:23:08.77,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’m going to give you my power’?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.77,0:23:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Because oftentimes we’re exhausted
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.17,0:23:14.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and we may feel like we’re unraveling.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.08,0:23:17.35,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jehovah is saying,\N‘I love you so much
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.35,0:23:21.69,Default,,0,0,0,,that I’m going to give you \Nthe power you need to accomplish my will.’
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.59,0:23:26.39,Default,,0,0,0,,You can see why Satan and Jehovah’s enemies
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.39,0:23:28.43,Default,,0,0,0,,have tried to hide Jehovah’s name
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.42,0:23:30.42,Default,,0,0,0,,—not just because it identified Him,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.43,0:23:33.57,Default,,0,0,0,,but because they wanted to obscure\Nthe power that that name has
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.56,0:23:36.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and what it means to us\Nand how it strengthens us.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.77,0:23:40.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But you know what else it also does?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.47,0:23:42.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It comforts us.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.80,0:23:46.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It can reassure our hearts.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.11,0:23:49.01,Default,,0,0,0,,It can allay our fears.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.01,0:23:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice how it did this\Nwith one of Jehovah’s servants.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.85,0:23:55.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s go back over to Jeremiah chapter 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.02,0:23:59.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember Jeremiah?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.19,0:24:02.43,Default,,0,0,0,,He was commissioned\Nwith a very difficult assignment,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.42,0:24:04.86,Default,,0,0,0,,representing Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.86,0:24:07.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And what did Jeremiah express to Jehovah?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.06,0:24:08.46,Default,,0,0,0,,He said: “I am but a boy.”
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.46,0:24:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,It was like he was saying:\N‘Jehovah, I’m inexperienced.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.77,0:24:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I know I have a spiritual foundation\Nyou’ve given me; you’ve trained me.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.90,0:24:18.10,Default,,0,0,0,,But I don’t know if I can handle this; I’m afraid.’
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.11,0:24:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What did Jehovah say to him to fortify him?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.88,0:24:22.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What did Jehovah cause him to become?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.88,0:24:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice verse 18, Jeremiah 1:18.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.68,0:24:33.65,Default,,0,0,0,,It says:\N“For today I have made you a fortified city,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.66,0:24:35.93,Default,,0,0,0,,“an iron pillar,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.92,0:24:39.99,Default,,0,0,0,,“and copper walls against all the land,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.00,0:24:42.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“toward the kings of Judah and her princes,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.46,0:24:45.56,Default,,0,0,0,,toward her priests and the people of the land.”
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.57,0:24:47.57,Default,,0,0,0,,“A fortified city”
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.57,0:24:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,—see, Jehovah says:\N‘I will strengthen you.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.57,0:24:51.47,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’ll make you like that iron pillar.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.47,0:24:54.97,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ll give you that inner strength\Nyou need to carry out your assignment.’
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.18,0:24:58.75,Default,,0,0,0,,But “copper walls”
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.75,0:25:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,—what was significant about copper walls?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.15,0:25:06.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it might be how Jehovah created copper.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.19,0:25:08.73,Default,,0,0,0,,What can copper do?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.72,0:25:13.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Copper at very high temperature will not buckle,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.73,0:25:16.47,Default,,0,0,0,,will not warp, will not lose its strength.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.70,0:25:20.04,Default,,0,0,0,,See, it’s as if Jehovah is saying,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.04,0:25:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Jeremiah, I will make it\Nso you can take the heat.’
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.34,0:25:27.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s what Jehovah is doing for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.51,0:25:29.51,Default,,0,0,0,,He will make it
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.51,0:25:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—make you—\Npossible to handle any situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.35,0:25:35.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And you notice those were copper walls\N—they fortified him.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.92,0:25:37.92,Default,,0,0,0,,They surrounded the city.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.92,0:25:40.92,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s as if mentally, emotionally, spiritually,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.92,0:25:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and physically Jehovah would give him
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.96,0:25:45.90,Default,,0,0,0,,whatever was needed\Nto carry out his assignment.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.36,0:25:50.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that fortified Jeremiah!
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.47,0:25:53.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you imagine\Nhow Jeremiah may have drawn upon this
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.60,0:25:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,as he dealt with challenges?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.20,0:25:58.90,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, when he was persecuted,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.91,0:26:00.91,Default,,0,0,0,,he was put in stocks.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.91,0:26:04.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that’s torture; that’s a form of torture.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.08,0:26:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you imagine Jeremiah’s prayer,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.18,0:26:10.85,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Jehovah, cause me\Nto become what I need to become
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.85,0:26:13.05,Default,,0,0,0,,to stay faithful to you’?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.05,0:26:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, did Jehovah block the pain?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.66,0:26:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,We don’t know.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.93,0:26:18.93,Default,,0,0,0,,But what we do know is
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.93,0:26:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jeremiah stayed faithful.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.00,0:26:23.10,Default,,0,0,0,,This experience did not break his will,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.10,0:26:26.37,Default,,0,0,0,,did not break his spirit,\Nnor did it break his integrity.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.80,0:26:30.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Or how about the time when Jeremiah
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.21,0:26:32.21,Default,,0,0,0,,had to go in front of the temple
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.21,0:26:34.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and in front of the priests and the leaders
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.21,0:26:36.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and had to tell them that their precious temple
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.21,0:26:37.71,Default,,0,0,0,,was going to be destroyed?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.71,0:26:38.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And he had to illustrate it
Dialogue: 0,0:26:38.91,0:26:41.38,Default,,0,0,0,,by slamming that clay vessel on the ground
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.38,0:26:43.72,Default,,0,0,0,,and watching it shatter.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.72,0:26:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you imagine Jeremiah’s prayer?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.85,0:26:47.35,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Jehovah, help me become
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.36,0:26:49.16,Default,,0,0,0,,‘what I need to to deliver this message.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.16,0:26:50.53,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Give me the poise.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.53,0:26:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Give me the courage.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.89,0:26:54.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Help me have that inner strength to do so.’
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.00,0:26:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And Jehovah did.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.00,0:27:02.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah was with Jeremiah time and time again.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.97,0:27:07.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the very name of Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.38,0:27:10.85,Default,,0,0,0,,makes it clear that you will succeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.85,0:27:14.15,Default,,0,0,0,,You will be able to carry out his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.15,0:27:16.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And you’ve been doing that.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.75,0:27:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,In your introductions to the family,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.76,0:27:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,we heard how Jehovah\Nwas causing you to become.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.09,0:27:28.36,Default,,0,0,0,,For example,\None of you talked about how as a young girl
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.36,0:27:32.20,Default,,0,0,0,,you and your sister\Nwere asked to leave the family home
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.20,0:27:34.94,Default,,0,0,0,,because of your relationship with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.94,0:27:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,What happened?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.94,0:27:40.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah caused you and others around you
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.01,0:27:41.55,Default,,0,0,0,,—your brothers and sisters—
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.54,0:27:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,to become what was necessary\Nto keep you close to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.51,0:27:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,One of you related how you were\Non a theocratic construction expansion project
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.65,0:27:55.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and you were assigned\Nto cut brick in the heat with all your gear on.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.53,0:27:59.53,Default,,0,0,0,,You said you maintained your joy.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.53,0:28:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.70,0:28:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Because Jehovah caused you to become.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.57,0:28:06.71,Default,,0,0,0,,One of you dear ones related to us
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.70,0:28:11.21,Default,,0,0,0,,how you had thought\Nyour service to Jehovah had no value to him.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.41,0:28:14.58,Default,,0,0,0,,You had lost your joy.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:14.58,0:28:16.58,Default,,0,0,0,,But what happened?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.58,0:28:20.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah caused someone to encourage you,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.12,0:28:22.56,Default,,0,0,0,,to strengthen you.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.55,0:28:24.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And one of you related how Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.62,0:28:28.96,Default,,0,0,0,,helped you serve\Nbeyond the capacity of your heart.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.23,0:28:33.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, Jehovah has caused all of you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.33,0:28:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,to become what is necessary to carry out his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.33,0:28:41.90,Default,,0,0,0,,So whenever you feel discouraged,\Nwhenever you feel afraid,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.90,0:28:44.54,Default,,0,0,0,,whenever you feel unqualified,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.54,0:28:46.54,Default,,0,0,0,,pray to Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:46.54,0:28:50.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Ask him to help you become\Nwhat is necessary to carry out his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.45,0:28:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Ask him to help you do whatever you need
Dialogue: 0,0:28:54.88,0:28:57.38,Default,,0,0,0,,so you can glorify his name.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.22,0:29:04.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider: When did Jehovah reveal
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.46,0:29:07.63,Default,,0,0,0,,this truth to the Israelites?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.63,0:29:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,It was right before they were\Nabout to face challenges.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.63,0:29:17.64,Default,,0,0,0,,When did Jehovah reveal this truth to us?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.64,0:29:22.38,Default,,0,0,0,,It was really with the revision\Nof the New World Translation.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.38,0:29:25.75,Default,,0,0,0,,It really helped bring it into focus\N—the power of his name—
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.75,0:29:27.99,Default,,0,0,0,,really, right before we are to be ushered
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.98,0:29:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,into Jehovah’s new world.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.19,0:29:33.93,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what trials will you face?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:33.92,0:29:37.06,Default,,0,0,0,,What challenges will you experience?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.06,0:29:40.20,Default,,0,0,0,,What will the great tribulation bring?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.20,0:29:42.57,Default,,0,0,0,,It doesn’t matter
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.56,0:29:44.86,Default,,0,0,0,,because you worship Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.87,0:29:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s his name\N—the God who causes to become.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.55,0:30:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we deeply appreciate\Nthat very fine talk, Brother Snyder.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.55,0:30:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we have Brother Donald Gordon,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.76,0:30:10.50,Default,,0,0,0,,who serves as a helper\Nto the Publishing Committee,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.49,0:30:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,with us to deliver the talk
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.49,0:30:15.16,Default,,0,0,0,,“Live in Sync With Jehovah.”
Dialogue: 0,0:30:17.17,0:30:19.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, for the last five months you dear students
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.97,0:30:24.47,Default,,0,0,0,,have been downloading a lot\Nof wonderful information about Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.47,0:30:28.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Now that the class has finished,\Nthe download is complete
Dialogue: 0,0:30:28.14,0:30:30.38,Default,,0,0,0,,—all synced up.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.38,0:30:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it may seem that way for the moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.11,0:30:37.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course,  Jehovah did not create us\Nlike simple computers
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.12,0:30:40.99,Default,,0,0,0,,where we just store away\Ninformation in our memories.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.99,0:30:43.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We were created “in his image.”
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.39,0:30:46.73,Default,,0,0,0,,So as we take in knowledge from Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.73,0:30:51.43,Default,,0,0,0,,we have the ability to absorb it\Nand then to reflect his image
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.43,0:30:54.70,Default,,0,0,0,,—to think like him, to feel like him.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:54.70,0:30:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We begin to act like him.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.01,0:31:02.01,Default,,0,0,0,,So he has given us\Nwhat we have here in his Word,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:02.01,0:31:04.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and he as well created us
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.51,0:31:08.98,Default,,0,0,0,,in our human capacity to assimilate his Word
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.98,0:31:11.72,Default,,0,0,0,,into the beautiful facets of his image,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:11.72,0:31:16.73,Default,,0,0,0,,and then we can truly be in sync with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.72,0:31:19.86,Default,,0,0,0,,But how does our being in sync with Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:31:19.86,0:31:23.83,Default,,0,0,0,,bring honor to him and joy to him?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.83,0:31:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, when we think of the various ones\Nwho are in sync with Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.57,0:31:31.34,Default,,0,0,0,,no doubt the foremost example is Jesus Christ.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.34,0:31:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything he did, everything he said,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.04,0:31:40.05,Default,,0,0,0,,every thought he had\Nwas in full harmony with his Father.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.05,0:31:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus said:\N“I cannot do a single thing of my own initiative.”
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.79,0:31:48.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes it’s like a husband and wife
Dialogue: 0,0:31:48.52,0:31:50.59,Default,,0,0,0,,who’ve been married a number of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.59,0:31:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,With just a glance, without a word,\Nthey know what the other one is thinking.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.23,0:31:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,They’re in sync.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.23,0:31:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps you’re thinking of two ice skaters
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.77,0:32:02.21,Default,,0,0,0,,flowing across the ice as one, in unison.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.44,0:32:06.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, one example of Jehovah and Jesus
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.04,0:32:08.14,Default,,0,0,0,,working in unison, in sync,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.14,0:32:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,is when the woman\Nwith the flow of blood was cured
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.35,0:32:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,by just touching the fringe of Jesus’ garment
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.22,0:32:16.66,Default,,0,0,0,,—one of our favorite miracles.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.65,0:32:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Recall that scene again, recorded here
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.09,0:32:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,at Mark 5:29, 30
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.89,0:32:27.36,Default,,0,0,0,,—Mark 5:29.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.36,0:32:29.76,Default,,0,0,0,,The woman\Nhas made her way through the crowd;
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.76,0:32:32.23,Default,,0,0,0,,she touches the garment, and then in verse 29:
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.23,0:32:35.47,Default,,0,0,0,,“Immediately her flow of blood dried up,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:35.47,0:32:39.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“and she sensed\Nin her body that she had been healed
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.01,0:32:41.31,Default,,0,0,0,,“of the grievous sickness.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.31,0:32:45.28,Default,,0,0,0,,“Immediately Jesus realized in himself
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.28,0:32:47.75,Default,,0,0,0,,“that power had gone out of him,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.75,0:32:50.15,Default,,0,0,0,,“and he turned around in the crowd and asked:
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.15,0:32:52.22,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Who touched my outer garments?’”
Dialogue: 0,0:32:53.29,0:32:57.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that moment\Nwhen that woman sensed that she was cured,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.33,0:33:01.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah and Jesus\Nwere working in complete harmony.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.26,0:33:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, until that moment,\NJesus may have been unaware
Dialogue: 0,0:33:04.80,0:33:09.54,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah was watching\Nthis woman with a desire to heal her.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.47,0:33:14.64,Default,,0,0,0,,I suppose that Jehovah\Ncould have just cured the woman on his own,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.64,0:33:17.84,Default,,0,0,0,,as it were, without Jesus even knowing.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.85,0:33:22.46,Default,,0,0,0,,But no, he chose to work through his Son,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.45,0:33:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,who he knew was working in harmony with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.32,0:33:30.56,Default,,0,0,0,,So when Jesus felt the power go out from him,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.56,0:33:33.13,Default,,0,0,0,,he naturally wanted to know who was cured
Dialogue: 0,0:33:33.13,0:33:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,—‘Who did my Father see that I did not see?’—
Dialogue: 0,0:33:36.03,0:33:38.87,Default,,0,0,0,,because they were working together in harmony.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.87,0:33:42.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And then seeing this woman,\Nrealizing that actually she was unclean
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.80,0:33:44.84,Default,,0,0,0,,and where she did not belong,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.84,0:33:47.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus was still\Nin complete agreement with his Father.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.81,0:33:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,He was in sync\Nwith Jehovah’s view of this woman
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.55,0:33:54.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and very happy\Nto have been involved in the cure of her
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.92,0:33:58.86,Default,,0,0,0,,—leaving us, of course, \Nwith one of our favorite accounts of Jesus’ life.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.05,0:34:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, what’s a lesson for us?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.52,0:34:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Whether we are at our work assignments,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.73,0:34:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,in our congregations, or out in the ministry,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:08.10,0:34:13.11,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to be in sync\Nwith how Jehovah views other people.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:13.10,0:34:17.10,Default,,0,0,0,,We often tend\Nto view others through our own eyes.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.11,0:34:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,This can be clouded\Nby our own human concerns and viewpoints,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.81,0:34:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,perhaps tainted by some misunderstandings
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.75,0:34:27.02,Default,,0,0,0,,or misconceptions or wrong information
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.01,0:34:31.18,Default,,0,0,0,,or perhaps\Nour need to be a little more forgiving.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.19,0:34:35.03,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, if any of those feelings\Nare tainting our judgment
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.02,0:34:38.46,Default,,0,0,0,,or relationships even in a small way,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.46,0:34:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,to that degree we are out of sync with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.90,0:34:46.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus and Jehovah\Nwere focused on this woman’s faith:
Dialogue: 0,0:34:46.97,0:34:48.97,Default,,0,0,0,,“Your faith has made you well.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:48.97,0:34:50.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Go in peace.”
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.97,0:34:53.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let us in every situation
Dialogue: 0,0:34:53.54,0:34:57.01,Default,,0,0,0,,strive to see others as Jehovah sees them.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.01,0:34:59.11,Default,,0,0,0,,This brings honor to Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.11,0:35:03.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and allows him\Nto use us in harmony with his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.89,0:35:08.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, there was another situation\Nwhere being in sync with his Father
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.39,0:35:11.39,Default,,0,0,0,,took more time and effort.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.39,0:35:14.49,Default,,0,0,0,,When Jesus\Nchose his 12 apostles, he, of course,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:14.50,0:35:17.74,Default,,0,0,0,,wanted to be in harmony with his Father,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:17.73,0:35:20.90,Default,,0,0,0,,but this did not happen with just a glance.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.90,0:35:25.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, Jesus had a very deep, \Nintimate knowledge of Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.74,0:35:29.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And these men that he was considering\N—he knew them well.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.01,0:35:33.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, this decision took hours of prayer
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.65,0:35:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,to arrive at the 12 apostles selected.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.32,0:35:39.76,Default,,0,0,0,,So it will be in performing your work
Dialogue: 0,0:35:39.75,0:35:42.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and making decisions in your assignments
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.36,0:35:46.43,Default,,0,0,0,,—you cannot simply rely\Non your knowledge of the Scriptures,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.43,0:35:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,as deep as it may be.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.86,0:35:53.40,Default,,0,0,0,,To make decisions,\Nwe must implore Jehovah in our prayers
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.40,0:35:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,—maybe many prayers—
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.40,0:35:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and our meditations.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:57.27,0:35:59.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t hold back from beseeching Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.94,0:36:02.11,Default,,0,0,0,,as you struggle for a decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.11,0:36:05.58,Default,,0,0,0,,But certainly, always relying,\Nof course, on his Word, the Bible
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.58,0:36:07.58,Default,,0,0,0,,—knowledge from his Word—
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.58,0:36:11.92,Default,,0,0,0,,prayers to our Father,\Nand then meditation on his will.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:14.86,0:36:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, you’ve learned in your class
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.06,0:36:21.60,Default,,0,0,0,,that the knowledge of Jehovah\Nis such a multifaceted gem.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.60,0:36:26.54,Default,,0,0,0,,There is an intriguing scripture \Nthat sheds further light on this thought
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.53,0:36:29.93,Default,,0,0,0,,here at Ephesians 3:19,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.37,0:36:36.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Ephesians 3:19.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:36.11,0:36:39.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It says “and to know the love of the Christ,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:39.55,0:36:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,which surpasses knowledge.”
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.98,0:36:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, now, how can knowing something
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.52,0:36:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,be more than the knowledge?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:49.02,0:36:53.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, you’ve learned here\Nthat the Greek term rendered “to know” means
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.66,0:36:58.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to know “practically, through experience.”
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.27,0:37:02.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, of course, the Gospel accounts\Nteach us much about Christ’s love.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.60,0:37:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,We come to know his patience,\Nhis humility, his willingness to forgive, etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:07.44,0:37:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,We read and we study that with delight.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.68,0:37:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,But to really know it,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.48,0:37:17.32,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s like, well, a skill that we might learn
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.32,0:37:19.42,Default,,0,0,0,,only after we actually do it.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.42,0:37:21.42,Default,,0,0,0,,For example,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.42,0:37:25.56,Default,,0,0,0,,a doctor goes to school to learn to be a doctor.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:25.56,0:37:29.36,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s lots of learning\Nand years of study involved,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.36,0:37:33.73,Default,,0,0,0,,but then when the studies are complete,\Nthey begin their internship.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.73,0:37:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,They begin making the rounds at the hospital.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.90,0:37:40.67,Default,,0,0,0,,They now begin taking part in this education
Dialogue: 0,0:37:40.68,0:37:42.45,Default,,0,0,0,,—what they learned from the books—
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.44,0:37:45.54,Default,,0,0,0,,and applying it to real-life situations.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.55,0:37:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The knowledge learned from this experience
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.48,0:37:52.35,Default,,0,0,0,,surpasses the knowledge learned in the books.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.35,0:37:56.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So we have studied the Christ;\Nwe do the bookwork; we have learned.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.92,0:38:00.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you Gilead students have had\Nthe amazing opportunity these last five months
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.83,0:38:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to read and study about his patience, his love,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.63,0:38:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,his forgiveness, humility, compassion.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.94,0:38:12.54,Default,,0,0,0,,You cherish that knowledge; you’re in sync
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.54,0:38:14.71,Default,,0,0,0,,—not quite yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.71,0:38:17.78,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, now we must do the internship;
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.78,0:38:22.05,Default,,0,0,0,,now we must take that knowledge\Nand make the rounds, as it were.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.05,0:38:25.49,Default,,0,0,0,,We go around the congregation;\Nwe interact with our workmates;
Dialogue: 0,0:38:25.49,0:38:27.49,Default,,0,0,0,,we go out in the field ministry.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.49,0:38:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,You deal with a sticky, difficult situation
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.99,0:38:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and put into practice\Nwhat you’ve learned from the Christ.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:36.00,0:38:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the way to get the full impact.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.00,0:38:42.54,Default,,0,0,0,,You’ve read and studied what he was thinking,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.54,0:38:46.54,Default,,0,0,0,,but now you know how he was feeling
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.54,0:38:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,—how it feels to unselfishly give\Nof oneself in behalf of others.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.21,0:38:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,How does it really feel\Nto act with humility as Jesus did?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.28,0:38:58.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Or you come to know how it really feels
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.22,0:39:01.76,Default,,0,0,0,,to forgive from the heart as Jesus did.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:01.76,0:39:04.46,Default,,0,0,0,,In this way, by experience
Dialogue: 0,0:39:04.46,0:39:07.16,Default,,0,0,0,,you come “to know the love of the Christ,”
Dialogue: 0,0:39:07.16,0:39:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and that ‘surpasses the knowledge.’
Dialogue: 0,0:39:10.20,0:39:15.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Now not only is what you know about God\Nand is treasured in your heart in sync
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.20,0:39:18.04,Default,,0,0,0,,but now your actions, your life,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:18.04,0:39:22.21,Default,,0,0,0,,and who you are is in sync with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:24.05,0:39:28.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed, like King David,\Nwho expressed in the 139th Psalm,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.52,0:39:31.56,Default,,0,0,0,,you dear students have found in God’s Word
Dialogue: 0,0:39:31.55,0:39:34.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the precious thoughts of Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:34.29,0:39:36.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Continue to search them out,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.72,0:39:40.62,Default,,0,0,0,,bring them to mind,\Ncherish them, and do them.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:40.63,0:39:45.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And then you\Nwill be living your life in sync with Jehovah.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:51.04,0:39:55.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we are very grateful\Nfor that heartfelt talk, Brother Gordon.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:55.28,0:39:59.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we go to one\Nof our Gilead instructors for the next talk;
Dialogue: 0,0:39:59.98,0:40:01.98,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s Brother Mark Noumair.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:01.98,0:40:04.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And he will speak on the subject
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.02,0:40:06.09,Default,,0,0,0,,“Offer Your Bow.”
Dialogue: 0,0:40:08.29,0:40:12.36,Default,,0,0,0,,At the age of 20, he was a natural leader,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.36,0:40:15.03,Default,,0,0,0,,commanding a thousand men.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:15.03,0:40:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,His tribe was legendary
Dialogue: 0,0:40:17.33,0:40:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,for their military prowess.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.60,0:40:22.27,Default,,0,0,0,,He was known as a skilled archer.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.27,0:40:25.34,Default,,0,0,0,,His bow never turned back from its target.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:25.34,0:40:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,He was the firstborn, favored prince
Dialogue: 0,0:40:28.31,0:40:31.95,Default,,0,0,0,,—courageous, loyal, loved by the people.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:31.95,0:40:35.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything was lining up perfectly
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.32,0:40:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,for Jonathan to become Israel’s next king
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.25,0:40:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,—everything except
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.29,0:40:44.99,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was not Jehovah’s choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:44.99,0:40:49.66,Default,,0,0,0,,So how would he react when he saw David
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.66,0:40:52.83,Default,,0,0,0,,receive Jehovah’s special favor?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:52.83,0:40:55.70,Default,,0,0,0,,How would he react when David
Dialogue: 0,0:40:55.70,0:40:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,was now transferred permanently
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.31,0:41:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,to the king’s house?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:00.64,0:41:03.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Would he be filled with envy, jealousy?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:03.31,0:41:05.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Would he feel threatened?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.31,0:41:09.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Would he work to assassinate David’s character?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:09.32,0:41:11.32,Default,,0,0,0,,After all,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:11.32,0:41:14.26,Default,,0,0,0,,David was 30 years younger than Jonathan
Dialogue: 0,0:41:14.26,0:41:17.43,Default,,0,0,0,,and came from a rather insignificant family.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.42,0:41:19.82,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what would Jonathan do?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:19.83,0:41:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what he did.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.83,0:41:24.33,Default,,0,0,0,,He did something remarkable.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:24.33,0:41:28.60,Default,,0,0,0,,And it’s found at 1 Samuel 18:3, 4.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.54,0:41:34.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is what we want you to think about:\Nwhat he did do and the application,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:34.18,0:41:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,because this is so valuable for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.71,0:41:42.22,Default,,0,0,0,,First Samuel 18:3, 4:
Dialogue: 0,0:41:43.42,0:41:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,“And Jonathan and David made a covenant,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:47.12,0:41:49.69,Default,,0,0,0,,because he loved him as himself.”
Dialogue: 0,0:41:49.69,0:41:51.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, note verse 4:
Dialogue: 0,0:41:51.69,0:41:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jonathan took off the sleeveless coat
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.76,0:41:57.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“that he wore and gave it to David,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.53,0:42:00.53,Default,,0,0,0,,“along with his gear, his sword,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:00.53,0:42:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,his bow, and his belt.”
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.10,0:42:07.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, this dramatic act of deep symbolism
Dialogue: 0,0:42:07.78,0:42:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,indicated that Jonathan would submit
Dialogue: 0,0:42:10.34,0:42:12.68,Default,,0,0,0,,his will to Jehovah’s will.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.68,0:42:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,He was going to humbly support David.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:15.55,0:42:17.55,Default,,0,0,0,,But think about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.55,0:42:21.32,Default,,0,0,0,,By offering his bow to David,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.32,0:42:25.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan was giving up\Na major part of his identity.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:25.16,0:42:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bible describes Jonathan as a manly warrior
Dialogue: 0,0:42:29.00,0:42:31.87,Default,,0,0,0,,—‘swifter than an eagle,’ ‘mightier than a lion.’
Dialogue: 0,0:42:31.87,0:42:34.07,Default,,0,0,0,,He was winning battles against the Philistines
Dialogue: 0,0:42:34.07,0:42:36.57,Default,,0,0,0,,before David was even born.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:36.57,0:42:40.27,Default,,0,0,0,,But was he worried\Nabout losing the respect of others?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.27,0:42:42.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Did he say: ‘What will people think of me?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:42.54,0:42:47.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Will I lose my credibility\Nif I support this younger David?’
Dialogue: 0,0:42:47.51,0:42:49.51,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:49.52,0:42:52.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Nor did he feel that Jehovah rejected him
Dialogue: 0,0:42:52.52,0:42:55.99,Default,,0,0,0,,because of the special favor upon David.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:55.99,0:42:59.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan’s bow and his other war equipment
Dialogue: 0,0:42:59.79,0:43:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,were his trademark,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:01.80,0:43:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,and that symbolized his military power.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:04.63,0:43:09.50,Default,,0,0,0,,But the bow did not make the man.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:09.50,0:43:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Love made the man
Dialogue: 0,0:43:11.51,0:43:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,—love for Jehovah, love for Jehovah’s choices.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:15.18,0:43:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what we’re highlighting.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:17.81,0:43:21.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And once Jonathan offered his bow,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:21.25,0:43:23.29,Default,,0,0,0,,he never retracted it,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:23.28,0:43:25.28,Default,,0,0,0,,even when he knew
Dialogue: 0,0:43:25.29,0:43:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,that David would be the next king.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.46,0:43:31.26,Default,,0,0,0,,He respected the divine arrangement,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:31.26,0:43:35.16,Default,,0,0,0,,and repeatedly Jonathan would support David.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:35.16,0:43:38.53,Default,,0,0,0,,He would reassure David,\N‘You are Jehovah’s choice.’
Dialogue: 0,0:43:40.00,0:43:42.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan was not insecure.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.60,0:43:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He was not afraid to appear insignificant.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:46.01,0:43:48.08,Default,,0,0,0,,He was not threatened to see David rise;
Dialogue: 0,0:43:48.08,0:43:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,nor did he view David as a rival to be eliminated.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:53.01,0:43:57.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, in human terms, this cost Jonathan.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:57.62,0:44:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,He lost the prospect of being king;
Dialogue: 0,0:44:00.39,0:44:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,he lost his close relationship with his father;
Dialogue: 0,0:44:04.63,0:44:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,he might have lost\Nsome stature in the eyes of men.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:09.20,0:44:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,But in spiritual terms, he gained.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:12.77,0:44:16.04,Default,,0,0,0,,His unselfish devotion to David
Dialogue: 0,0:44:16.04,0:44:18.78,Default,,0,0,0,,received honorable mention in God’s Word,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:18.77,0:44:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,which never would have happened\Nhad he resisted Jehovah’s choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:22.68,0:44:25.25,Default,,0,0,0,,We wouldn’t even be talking about this right now
Dialogue: 0,0:44:25.25,0:44:27.35,Default,,0,0,0,,if he took a fleshly view
Dialogue: 0,0:44:27.35,0:44:30.35,Default,,0,0,0,,of Jehovah’s divine arrangement.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:30.35,0:44:32.85,Default,,0,0,0,,So this is your first big lesson:
Dialogue: 0,0:44:32.85,0:44:36.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Don’t measure your worth by your job title.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:38.33,0:44:40.37,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s your love of Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:44:40.36,0:44:43.16,Default,,0,0,0,,—that’s what makes you so valuable.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:43.16,0:44:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,A spiritual person is a most powerful tool
Dialogue: 0,0:44:46.57,0:44:49.97,Default,,0,0,0,,in the hands of God, and this is what you are.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:49.97,0:44:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,So how can you imitate Jonathan?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:52.74,0:44:55.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Offer your bow
Dialogue: 0,0:44:55.31,0:44:59.75,Default,,0,0,0,,by showing your support\Nof Jehovah’s organizational decisions,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:59.75,0:45:03.29,Default,,0,0,0,,even if it means giving up something you love
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.28,0:45:05.52,Default,,0,0,0,,or want to cling to.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:05.52,0:45:07.66,Default,,0,0,0,,For example,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:07.65,0:45:11.05,Default,,0,0,0,,some of you have been given\Nnew country assignments,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.06,0:45:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,and yet you might not have planned
Dialogue: 0,0:45:13.36,0:45:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,on moving to another country.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:15.56,0:45:20.23,Default,,0,0,0,,You were content where you were;\Nyou were happy doing what you were doing.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.23,0:45:22.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:22.24,0:45:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for your unselfish support\Nof the decisions made
Dialogue: 0,0:45:26.47,0:45:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,to advance Kingdom interests globally.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:28.84,0:45:31.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:31.01,0:45:34.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps you’ve been trained in some capacity
Dialogue: 0,0:45:34.28,0:45:36.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—something you really enjoy.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:36.35,0:45:40.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet now someone else\Nis assigned to do that job.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:40.39,0:45:42.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you, like Jonathan,
Dialogue: 0,0:45:42.39,0:45:45.96,Default,,0,0,0,,put your heart into supporting and reassuring
Dialogue: 0,0:45:45.96,0:45:49.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the new person that took your job?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:49.50,0:45:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And how about you as a sister?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:52.20,0:45:55.30,Default,,0,0,0,,What about if a new sister comes and gets
Dialogue: 0,0:45:55.30,0:45:57.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the job assignment you love, you cherish?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:57.81,0:46:00.58,Default,,0,0,0,,You wake up every day ‘I love my job!’
Dialogue: 0,0:46:00.57,0:46:02.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and now you’re asked to train her.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.74,0:46:04.74,Default,,0,0,0,,What will you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:04.75,0:46:06.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you offer your bow?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.68,0:46:12.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Or the sister gets the office that you dreamed of
Dialogue: 0,0:46:12.05,0:46:13.62,Default,,0,0,0,,—the one with the window.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:13.62,0:46:16.82,Default,,0,0,0,,There it is.\NYou had your eyes set on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:16.82,0:46:18.52,Default,,0,0,0,,You might have seniority.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:18.53,0:46:21.37,Default,,0,0,0,,She could be younger than you,\Nbut perhaps oversight
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.36,0:46:23.80,Default,,0,0,0,,took other factors into consideration
Dialogue: 0,0:46:23.80,0:46:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,that you were not aware of.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:25.80,0:46:27.80,Default,,0,0,0,,What will you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:27.80,0:46:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,What will all of you do in these situations?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:30.30,0:46:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Will you accept the fact that supporting decisions
Dialogue: 0,0:46:33.71,0:46:35.71,Default,,0,0,0,,by the organization at times
Dialogue: 0,0:46:35.71,0:46:38.48,Default,,0,0,0,,involves sacrifices on your part?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:39.91,0:46:42.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, let your love for Jehovah
Dialogue: 0,0:46:42.35,0:46:46.02,Default,,0,0,0,,mean more than your cherished work assignment.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.02,0:46:49.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is a very, very big lesson\N—lesson number one—
Dialogue: 0,0:46:49.79,0:46:52.33,Default,,0,0,0,,and very important for you to think about,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:52.33,0:46:56.13,Default,,0,0,0,,offering your bow in this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:56.13,0:46:58.17,Default,,0,0,0,,You’ve already shown this spirit.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:58.17,0:47:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re just reinforcing something
Dialogue: 0,0:47:00.50,0:47:03.04,Default,,0,0,0,,that you need to hear prior to your departure.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:05.14,0:47:07.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I want you to think about this for a moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:09.91,0:47:12.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Compare Jonathan’s good example
Dialogue: 0,0:47:12.91,0:47:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,with that of his brother Ish-bosheth.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:17.92,0:47:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,When Saul died,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:20.02,0:47:23.39,Default,,0,0,0,,2 Samuel 2:8 says
Dialogue: 0,0:47:23.39,0:47:25.49,Default,,0,0,0,,that his general, Abner,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:25.49,0:47:28.86,Default,,0,0,0,,made Ish-bosheth king
Dialogue: 0,0:47:28.86,0:47:31.33,Default,,0,0,0,,—no loyalty to Jehovah’s choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:31.33,0:47:34.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And Ish-bosheth agreed, ‘I want that.’
Dialogue: 0,0:47:34.43,0:47:37.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Ish-bosheth craved position,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:37.80,0:47:42.41,Default,,0,0,0,,which led to a civil war, which led to problems.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:42.41,0:47:45.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, instead of Ish-bosheth offering his bow
Dialogue: 0,0:47:45.61,0:47:48.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and his war equipment to David,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:48.62,0:47:50.86,Default,,0,0,0,,2 Samuel chapter 2
Dialogue: 0,0:47:50.85,0:47:54.62,Default,,0,0,0,,describes how he provoked war with David,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:54.62,0:47:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,which resulted in bloodshed
Dialogue: 0,0:47:56.72,0:48:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and the death of 380 men in Israel.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:00.59,0:48:04.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Ish-bosheth’s heart wasn’t with David.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:04.03,0:48:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,That was Jehovah’s choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:06.13,0:48:08.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He was unlike his brother Jonathan.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:10.07,0:48:14.14,Default,,0,0,0,,But now imagine if Jonathan was still alive
Dialogue: 0,0:48:14.14,0:48:17.41,Default,,0,0,0,,when Saul died and Abner\Nnow comes to Jonathan and says:
Dialogue: 0,0:48:17.41,0:48:19.61,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Jonathan, I want you to be king.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:19.61,0:48:21.88,Default,,0,0,0,,You’d make a great king.’
Dialogue: 0,0:48:21.88,0:48:23.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Would Jonathan have agreed?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:23.65,0:48:26.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Would he have then said,\N‘Give me my bow back’ and retract it
Dialogue: 0,0:48:26.79,0:48:30.26,Default,,0,0,0,,and take it back and tell David:\N‘No, I feigned loyalty to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:30.26,0:48:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what I really wanted.\NI want to be king’?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:32.79,0:48:34.79,Default,,0,0,0,,No. No.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:34.80,0:48:36.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan wouldn’t have done that.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:36.56,0:48:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:38.33,0:48:41.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Because he gave not just his bow to David,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:41.44,0:48:44.44,Default,,0,0,0,,he gave not just his war equipment to David (no),
Dialogue: 0,0:48:44.44,0:48:47.88,Default,,0,0,0,,he gave his very heart to Jehovah’s choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:47.87,0:48:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s the beautiful thing about him.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:50.14,0:48:52.71,Default,,0,0,0,,The difference between Jonathan,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:52.71,0:48:56.88,Default,,0,0,0,,who sees an opportunity\Nto support Jehovah’s cause,
Dialogue: 0,0:48:56.88,0:49:01.15,Default,,0,0,0,,and Ish-bosheth,\Nwho never thought for a moment
Dialogue: 0,0:49:01.15,0:49:05.86,Default,,0,0,0,,about how Jehovah God\Nwas directing David, is striking.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:06.93,0:49:09.63,Default,,0,0,0,,And the results speak for themselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:09.63,0:49:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan was loved and honored.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:12.77,0:49:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Ish-bosheth was hated and murdered.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:19.34,0:49:21.98,Default,,0,0,0,,When Jonathan died,
Dialogue: 0,0:49:21.98,0:49:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,David was so deeply grieved
Dialogue: 0,0:49:24.78,0:49:27.12,Default,,0,0,0,,by the loss of his dear friend
Dialogue: 0,0:49:27.11,0:49:29.91,Default,,0,0,0,,that he was moved to do something.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:29.92,0:49:32.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And what he did is recorded
Dialogue: 0,0:49:32.92,0:49:37.96,Default,,0,0,0,,at 2 Samuel 1:17, 18.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:37.96,0:49:40.63,Default,,0,0,0,,I’d like to read this to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:40.63,0:49:44.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Second Samuel 1:17, 18:
Dialogue: 0,0:49:47.53,0:49:51.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“Then David chanted this dirge [or this song]
Dialogue: 0,0:49:51.04,0:49:55.88,Default,,0,0,0,,“over Saul and his son Jonathan and said
Dialogue: 0,0:49:55.88,0:49:58.18,Default,,0,0,0,,“that the people of Judah should be taught
Dialogue: 0,0:49:58.18,0:50:02.62,Default,,0,0,0,,the dirge [the song] called ‘The Bow.’”
Dialogue: 0,0:50:02.62,0:50:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“The Bow.”
Dialogue: 0,0:50:04.65,0:50:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Could David have had in mind the bow
Dialogue: 0,0:50:07.99,0:50:12.16,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jonathan gave him\Nat the beginning of their friendship?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:12.16,0:50:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan supported\Nthe nation without demanding
Dialogue: 0,0:50:15.36,0:50:18.30,Default,,0,0,0,,that he receive high rank, or position.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:18.30,0:50:20.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Jonathan was so loyal.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.47,0:50:23.64,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a powerful lesson that David never forgot,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:23.64,0:50:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and neither did he want\Nthe sons of Judah to forget,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:26.47,0:50:30.47,Default,,0,0,0,,because he instructed\Nthat they all learn this song by heart.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:31.85,0:50:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Offering your bow
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.95,0:50:38.62,Default,,0,0,0,,is a powerful word picture.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:38.62,0:50:41.82,Default,,0,0,0,,When you continue to work in the background
Dialogue: 0,0:50:41.82,0:50:43.82,Default,,0,0,0,,(work quietly in the background),
Dialogue: 0,0:50:43.82,0:50:46.96,Default,,0,0,0,,in loyal support of Jehovah’s choices
Dialogue: 0,0:50:46.96,0:50:50.50,Default,,0,0,0,,despite the cost,\Ndespite the human imperfections,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:50.50,0:50:53.90,Default,,0,0,0,,despite the disappointments,\Ndespite the perceived injustices,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:53.90,0:50:55.90,Default,,0,0,0,,you don’t worry about all of that.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:55.90,0:50:59.17,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s simply the ebb and flow of life.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.17,0:51:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Pick yourself up; keep on moving; grow mighty;
Dialogue: 0,0:51:02.38,0:51:06.15,Default,,0,0,0,,become a living example\Nto the brotherhood in loyalty.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:06.15,0:51:08.62,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s what you’ve been trained to do.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:08.62,0:51:10.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And you will receive
Dialogue: 0,0:51:10.62,0:51:12.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s attention and favor
Dialogue: 0,0:51:12.62,0:51:14.62,Default,,0,0,0,,just as Jonathan did.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:15.62,0:51:19.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah did not merely dismiss\NJonathan as a would-have-been king.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.96,0:51:21.63,Default,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:21.63,0:51:25.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather, he took note of Jonathan’s loyal support
Dialogue: 0,0:51:25.07,0:51:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,and had his wonderful example embedded,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:28.17,0:51:31.17,Default,,0,0,0,,etched, into his inspired Word.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:33.47,0:51:36.41,Default,,0,0,0,,So as you go to your assignment,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:36.41,0:51:38.91,Default,,0,0,0,,what is your bow?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:39.91,0:51:42.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone has one.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:42.05,0:51:45.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it your cherished work assignment?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:45.29,0:51:50.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it that privilege that you have been given\Nthat few others enjoy?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:50.12,0:51:52.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it the responsibility
Dialogue: 0,0:51:52.23,0:51:55.80,Default,,0,0,0,,that requires many to consult you for direction?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:55.80,0:51:57.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, think about this:
Dialogue: 0,0:51:57.96,0:51:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,The time will come
Dialogue: 0,0:51:59.97,0:52:03.21,Default,,0,0,0,,when someone is put in a leading role,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:03.20,0:52:06.44,Default,,0,0,0,,and you will be asked to support that person,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.44,0:52:09.18,Default,,0,0,0,,work under that person, help that person.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:09.18,0:52:12.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And when that time comes, ask yourself,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:12.25,0:52:14.85,Default,,0,0,0,,‘What will I do?’
Dialogue: 0,0:52:14.85,0:52:18.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And not just you brothers, you sisters too,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:18.99,0:52:21.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I mean, you wives, will you support?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:21.19,0:52:23.23,Default,,0,0,0,,will the wife support as well?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:23.22,0:52:25.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Single sisters, will you support the arrangement?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:25.56,0:52:26.83,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s the point.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:26.83,0:52:30.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Ask yourself: ‘Will I offer my bow like Jonathan?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:30.26,0:52:32.26,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Will I offer it freely?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:32.27,0:52:36.34,Default,,0,0,0,,‘Will I offer it generously to anyone chosen
Dialogue: 0,0:52:36.34,0:52:40.21,Default,,0,0,0,,for a role of responsibility\Nwithin God’s organization?’
Dialogue: 0,0:52:40.21,0:52:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And be assured\Nthat Jehovah in turn will offer you
Dialogue: 0,0:52:44.31,0:52:47.35,Default,,0,0,0,,—offer you an unimaginable treasure.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:47.35,0:52:50.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And that treasure is his favor and approval.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:50.85,0:52:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah’s favor and approval
Dialogue: 0,0:52:52.85,0:52:54.85,Default,,0,0,0,,—what is better than that?—
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.86,0:52:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,now and life in the new world.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:58.23,0:53:00.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And when you get to the new world,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:00.46,0:53:02.66,Default,,0,0,0,,be sure to look for the one
Dialogue: 0,0:53:02.66,0:53:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,who inspired you to offer your bow.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:20.11,0:53:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we thank you, Brother Noumair,\Nvery much for that encouraging talk.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:24.28,0:53:29.29,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, we’ve enjoyed a series\Nof wonderful talks this morning, haven’t we?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:30.39,0:53:33.43,Default,,0,0,0,,What an encouraging program thus far!
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.43,0:53:35.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And in the upcoming weeks,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:35.43,0:53:39.64,Default,,0,0,0,,look for Parts 2 and 3 of the graduation program.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:39.63,0:53:42.47,Default,,0,0,0,,They’ll be found under Latest Videos
Dialogue: 0,0:53:42.47,0:53:47.14,Default,,0,0,0,,or under the Video on Demand segment\Nof JW Broadcasting.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:47.14,0:53:49.98,Default,,0,0,0,,We’ll conclude this month’s program
Dialogue: 0,0:53:49.98,0:53:54.02,Default,,0,0,0,,by traveling to the tropical island\Nof Kosrae in Micronesia.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:55.08,0:53:57.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Located in the Pacific Ocean,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:57.08,0:54:01.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Kosrae is filled\Nwith dense jungles, mangroves,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:01.22,0:54:05.39,Default,,0,0,0,,picturesque beaches,\Nand is surrounded by beautiful coral.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:05.39,0:54:07.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Many on the island work in the tourism,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:07.93,0:54:11.30,Default,,0,0,0,,fishing, or agricultural industries.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:11.30,0:54:13.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Although the official language\Nof Kosrae is English,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:13.87,0:54:17.07,Default,,0,0,0,,there’s a remote translation office here.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:17.90,0:54:21.74,Default,,0,0,0,,One brother and four sisters\Nassist with translating literature
Dialogue: 0,0:54:21.74,0:54:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,into Kosraean.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:23.88,0:54:26.35,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s one congregation on Kosrae
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.35,0:54:30.15,Default,,0,0,0,,with 2 field missionaries, 2 special pioneers,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:30.15,0:54:34.55,Default,,0,0,0,,and 2 regular pioneers,\Nand a total of about 15 publishers.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:35.76,0:54:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,They preach\Nto the over 6,000 inhabitants of the island.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:39.26,0:54:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And their hard work is bearing fruit.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:42.70,0:54:45.77,Default,,0,0,0,,For example, in 2018,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:45.77,0:54:50.01,Default,,0,0,0,,there were 82 in attendance\Nat the Memorial celebration
Dialogue: 0,0:54:50.00,0:54:53.77,Default,,0,0,0,,and a peak of 65\Nattended the regional convention.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:53.77,0:54:55.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And in 2018,
